  doi = {10.2307/2077133},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Searle develops a theory of social ontology based on
  collective intentionality and constitutive rules. Social facts are
  created through collective assignment of status functions via the
  formula "X counts as Y in context C." Argues that institutional facts
  (including traditions) exist only through collective recognition and
  acceptance, distinguishing "we-intentions" from individual intentions.
  Social reality is both objective (independent of individual attitudes)
  and ontologically subjective (dependent on collective attitudes).

  RELEVANCE: Provides the foundational framework for understanding
  tradition as socially constructed yet objectively real. Searle's
  status function account explains how traditions acquire authority
  through collective recognition. His distinction between brute and
  institutional facts illuminates tradition's dependence on collective
  intentionality rather than physical properties. However, leaves open
  questions about temporal persistence and intergenerational transmission
  that are central to tradition.

  POSITION: Establishes social constructionism grounded in collective
  intentionality—most influential account of social ontology for analyzing
  tradition as institutional phenomenon.
  },
