  pages = {85--105},
  doi = {10.1111/J.2041-6962.2006.TB00032.X},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: List and Pettit develop functionalist account of group
  agency. Groups can be agents when they meet functional criteria:
  representational states, motivational states, and capacity to process
  information and act. Group agency supervenes on but is not reducible to
  individual states. Groups can have attitudes and intentions distinct
  from members' attitudes through aggregation procedures. Argues groups
  are genuine agents capable of belief, desire, and intentional action.

  RELEVANCE: Provides framework for understanding how traditions enable
  collective agency. Groups structured by traditions can have collective
  intentions and responsibilities irreducible to members. Their
  supervenience thesis explains how traditions persist through membership
  changes—collective properties depend on but transcend individual
  properties. However, focus on synchronic groups leaves questions about
  diachronic collective agency across generations that traditions involve.

  POSITION: Functionalist group agency theory—influential account showing
  how collectives can be genuine agents, applicable to tradition-bearing
  groups.
  },
